  "text": "Few studies have investigated the temporal profile of exercise-mediated adaptations after stroke. Based on studies of exercise rehabilitation in the frail elderly, we studied the profile of fitness and mobility function gains across 6 months of training, [CITATION_1] a much longer therapeutic duration than is typical for most stroke rehabilitation programs. Our results show that the time profiles of cardiovascular fitness gains with treadmill exercise training are progressive and nearly equal across the initial 3 months and from the 3rd to the 6th month of training (FIG. 5) . There is no evidence of plateau, suggesting that training even beyond 6 months may produce further benefits in peak fitness levels. In addition, treadmill exercise also improves 6-minute walk performance and self-reported indices of functional mobility across 6 months, with greater gains in 6-minute walk occurring within the initial 3 months of training (FIG. 6) .",
